p2
VHolding high promise
p3
sVnews
p4
VThe management committee of Sri Vedamatha Gayatri Samsthan, Seethammadhara,headed by P. Gopalakrishna Murty, featured two vocal recitals as part of Navaratri celebrations. Sreerangam Suhasini, who is in her early teens, sang first in the company of her guruChaganti Uma&#8217;s daughter, Ramya Kiranmayi, who was on the violin, and Kamesh on the mridangam.Starting withGirirajasuthatanayain Bangla,  she renderedSree Saraswathi(Aarabhi), which was adorned with a briefswarakalpana,Sarojadalanetri(Sankarabharanam) with impressivealapanaandswarakalpanain the two tempos,Ramunimaravakame(Kedaragoula) and the concluding piece, athillana,in Pharaj. She sang with such perfection that no one in the audience, including connoisseurs of music, could make out that it was her maiden venture on the stage.Later, the recital by Moola Sridevi, as young as Suhasini, but with good experience on the stage, was engrossing. Starting with avarnamin Darbar, she mellifluously renderedEkadantam(Bilhari),Seethamma(Vasantha) withswaram,Kamalamba(Anandabhairavi),Sree Saraswathi(Maanji),Needucharanapankajamule(Kalyani) expansively withalapana,neravuandswaramin the two tempos,Narayanathe(Behag) and athillanain Kharaharapriya like a seasoned professional. Kiranmayi on the violin and Kamesh on the mridangam both proved to be her peers.
